    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "ok so the lawyer is basically the guardian of the money. sounds a bit stressful though... what happens if the lawyer makes a mistake or if there's like a disagreement about the funds while they are sitting there? is there any risk of the money just disappearing or being mishandled?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You are absolutely right to feel a bit stressed, but in Ontario, the rules for lawyers holding funds are incredibly strict to prevent exactly that kind of mistake or disappearance. The lawyer's trust account is segregated from their personal funds, meaning they legally cannot touch that money for their own use, even if they make a mistake. If a disagreement arises, the dispute is usually resolved by the Real Estate Board of Ontario (REBO) or through a court order, ensuring the funds stay safe until the issue is settled.\n\nThink of it like a high-security vault guarded by a very organized, rule-following team; if a mistake happens, there are specific protocols to fix it immediately. It's a system designed so that the money never just vanishes.\n\nWould you like to know what happens if the buyer and seller can't agree on the final price before the lawyer releases the funds?",
